QUALIFICATION: Of the two pinned specimens in ANIC, we did not mount the one from Coogee Bay as it lacks its head and abdomen and has a wing colour pattern different from the other. The syntype from Illawarra district, which we mounted, retains all body parts except the tarsi. Assigned to unplaced Cecidomyiinae by Gagné (2004: 276), it belongs to Contarinia but lacks distinctive morphological characters to distinguish it from other congeneric females (Kolesik & Gagné 2016).

QUALIFICATION: Hendel (1908) was the first after Meigen (1800) to give characters to differentiate the taxon (reproducing Meigen?s characters) and to treat Polyxena as valid, which makes the name available from that work with Meigen as author. Hendel (1908) did not include any species. Stone (1941) was the first to include a species, Cordyla fusca Meigen, 1804, which is the type species by subsequent designation. Cordyla fusca Meigen, 1804 is currently treated in Cordyla Meigen, 1803, which makes Polyxena Meigen in Hendel, 1908 a junior synonym of Cordyla Meigen, 1803

QUALIFICATION: Hendel (1908: 48) was the first after Meigen (1800) to give characters to differentiate the taxon (reproducing Meigen?s characters) and to treat Fungivora as valid, which makes the name available from that work with Meigen as author. Hendel (1908) included two nominal species. Coquillett (1910: 545) designated the second of these two, Tipula agarici Villers, 1789, which is the type species by subsequent designation. Tipula agarici Villers, 1789 is currently treated in Mycetophila Meigen, 1803, which makes Fungivora Meigen in Hendel, 1908 a junior synonym of Mycetophila Meigen, 1803 (see Evenhuis & Pope 2017)

QUALIFICATION: Preoccupied by Euphrosyne Gray, 1866 and Euphrosyne Buchecker, 1880. Hendel (1908: 47) was the first after Meigen (1800) to give characters to differentiate the taxon (reproducing Meigen?s characters) and to treat Euphrosyne as valid, which makes the name available from that work with Meigen as author. Hendel?s (1908) single species, given as ?Tip. longicornis??, is questionably included and, as such, is not allowed under Article 67.2.5 of the Code. The first included species fulfilling the conditions of the Code was in Coquillett (1910: 542) who selected Macrocera lutea Meigen, 1804 as type species by subsequent designation. Macrocera lutea Meigen, 1804 is currently treated in Macrocera Meigen, 1803, which makes Euphrosyne Meigen in Hendel, 1908 a junior synonym of Macrocera Meigen, 1803 (Evenhuis & Pape 2017)

QUALIFICATION: Preoccupied by Philia Schiödte, 1842 and Philia Koch, 1846. Hendel (1908) was the first after Meigen (1800) to give characters to differentiate the taxon (reproducing Meigen?s characters) and to treat Philia as valid, which makes the name available from that work with Meigen as author. Hendel (1908) did not include any species. Coquillett (1910a: 588) was the first to include a species: Tipula febrilis Linnaeus, 1758, which is the type species by subsequent designation. Tipula febrilis Linnaeus, 1758 is currently treated in Dilophus Meigen, 1803, which makes Philia Meigen in Hendel, 1908 a junior synonym of Dilophus Meigen, 1803

QUALIFICATION: non Lycoria Meigen, 1800. Latreille (1802) was the first subsequent usage of Lycoria after Meigen (1800) where Lycoria was placed in synonymy with Tipula Linnaeus, 1758, sensu lato, and included a single species: Tipula fenestralis Scopoli, 1763 [as ?Tipula fenestrarum Scop.?]. The name was made available from Latreille (1802) by subsequent usage as a valid name in Hendel (1908). Tipula fenestralis Scopoli, 1763 is currently treated as a species of Sylvicola Harris, 1776, which makes Lycoria Latreille, 1802 a junior synonym of Sylvicola Harris, 1776. Previous workers (e.g., Coquillett 1910; Stone 1941; Melville 1960; Sabrosky 1999) missed the first inclusion of a species in Latreille (1802) and believed that Hendel?s (1908) inclusion of Tipula thomae Linnaeus, 1767 [as ?Hirtea thomae F.?] was the first included species. Tipula thomae Linnaeus, 1767 is currently treated in Sciara Meigen, 1803 [teste Steffan (1989: 149)], which led previous workers dealing with Meigen names to believe Lycoria was synonymous with Sciara Meigen, 1803 (Evenhuis & Pape 2017)
